We will use OpenSSL to create a private key and a self-signed certificate valid for 365 days, specifically generated for your local domain name my-app.com.

Run this command on your controlplane terminal:

Bash
openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
  -keyout ~/kube/networking/Ingress/my-app.key \
    -out ~/kube/networking/Ingress/my-app.crt \
      -subj "/CN=my-app.com/O=LocalLab"
      This creates two files in your folder: my-app.key (your private key) and my-app.crt (your public certificate).

      Step 2: Store the Certificate in a Kubernetes Secret
      An Ingress resource cannot read raw certificate files directly from the Linux hard drive. It requires them to be securely stored inside the cluster as a TLS Secret.

      Run this command to import your fresh keys into your active namespace:

      Bash
      kubectl create secret tls my-app-tls-secret \
        --cert=/home/system/kube/networking/tls/my-app.crt \
          --key=/home/system/kube/networking/tls/my-app.key
          Step 3: Update the Ingress Resource with the TLS Block

[19:29:17] system@controlplane:~/kube/networking/tls$ curl -k -H "Host: my-app.com" https://192.168.31.157:32266/app1
Hello , Welcome to App1
[19:30:07] system@controlplane:~/kube/networking/tls$ curl -k -H "Host: my-app.com" https://192.168.31.157:32266/app2
Hello, Welcome to App2


Patching Ingress TLS Configurations
What it is: An inline method to attach, modify, or swap out SSL/TLS termination certificates on an existing Ingress resource.

What it does: Updates the spec.tls block using a JSON patch to secure external HTTP traffic with HTTPS without needing to redeploy or edit the entire Ingress manifest.

Imperative Commands
1. Add or Overwrite the TLS Secret and Host
If you want to completely replace or set the TLS configuration, you can use a Strategic Merge Patch. This will update (or add) the first element in the TLS array:



kubectl patch ingress advanced-ingress -p '{"spec":{"tls":[{"hosts":["app.exam.com"],"secretName":"domain-tls-secret"}]}}'

Imperative Commands (Strategic Merge Patching)
Bash
# 1. Scale a deployment instantly by patching the replica count
kubectl patch deployment web-deploy -p '{"spec":{"replicas":5}}'

# 2. Update a running container's image tag using inline nested JSON
kubectl patch deployment web-deploy -p '{"spec":{"template":{"spec":{"containers":[{"name":"nginx","image":"nginx:1.19.0"}]}}}}'

# 3. Patch a Pod to add or change a label dynamically
kubectl patch pod exam-pod -p '{"metadata":{"labels":{"tier":"frontend"}}}'

# 4. Inject an environment variable into a deployment's container template
kubectl patch deployment web-deploy -p '{"spec":{"template":{"spec":{"containers":[{"name":"nginx","env":[{"name":"ENV_MODE","value":"production"}]}]}}}}'

# 5. Update resource memory requests and limits for a container template
kubectl patch deployment web-deploy -p '{"spec":{"template":{"spec":{"containers":[{"name":"nginx","resources":{"requests":{"memory":"128Mi"},"limits":{"memory":"256Mi"}}}]}}}}'

# 6. Patch an Ingress resource to switch its backend service target port
kubectl patch ingress advanced-ingress --type='json' -p='[{"op": "replace", "path": "/spec/rules/0/http/paths/0/backend/service/port/number", "value": 8080}]'
